                        <div id="q2" class="accordion-collapse collapse" data-bs-parent="#faqTeslaModelY">
                            <div class="accordion-body">
                                The <span class="font-weight-700">Insured Declared Value (IDV)</span> is the current market value of your bike and represents the maximum claim payout you can receive for theft or total loss. The <span class="font-weight-700">Premium</span> is the annual fee you pay to the insurance company to keep the policy active. A higher IDV generally leads to a higher premium.
                            </div>
                        </div>
                    </div>

                    <div class="accordion-item">
                        <h3 class="accordion-header">
                            <button class="accordion-button collapsed" type="button" data-bs-toggle="collapse" data-bs-target="#q3" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="q3">
                                3. Can I buy a Zero Depreciation cover for an old bike?
                            </button>
                        </h3>
                        <div id="q3" class="accordion-collapse collapse" data-bs-parent="#faqTeslaModelY">
                            <div class="accordion-body">
                                Zero Depreciation cover is typically only available for new bikes, often up to the first three to five years of the vehicle's age. This is because, beyond this period, the vehicle's depreciation rate becomes too high for insurers to offer full depreciation waiver on all parts.
                            </div>
                        </div>
                    </div>

                    <div class="accordion-item">
                        <h3 class="accordion-header">
                            <button class="accordion-button collapsed" type="button" data-bs-toggle="collapse" data-bs-target="#q4" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="q4">
                                4. What happens to my No Claim Bonus (NCB) if my policy lapses?
                            </button>
                        </h3>
                        <div id="q4" class="accordion-collapse collapse" data-bs-parent="#faqTeslaModelY">
                            <div class="accordion-body">
                                If your bike insurance policy lapses (expires without renewal), the No Claim Bonus (NCB) that you had accumulated will typically be reset to zero. To prevent this, it is crucial to renew the policy before the expiration date, or within a grace period if offered by the insurer.
                            </div>
                        </div>
                    </div>

                    <div class="accordion-item">
                        <h3 class="accordion-header">
                            <button class="accordion-button collapsed" type="button" data-bs-toggle="collapse" data-bs-target="#q5" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="q5">
                                5. Should I choose a low IDV to reduce my premium?
                            </button>
                        </h3>
                        <div id="q5" class="accordion-collapse collapse" data-bs-parent="#faqTeslaModelY">
                            <div class="accordion-body">
                                While opting for a lower IDV will reduce the premium, it is generally <span class="font-weight-700">not recommended</span>. The IDV is the maximum amount you will receive if your bike is stolen or totaled. Choosing an artificially low IDV means you will face a significant financial loss if you have to replace your bike after such an incident.
                            </div>
                        </div>
                    </div>

                    <div class="accordion-item">
                        <h3 class="accordion-header">
                            <button class="accordion-button collapsed" type="button" data-bs-toggle="collapse" data-bs-target="#q6" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="q6">
                                6. Is Personal Accident (PA) Cover for the Owner-Driver optional?
                            </button>
                        </h3>
                        <div id="q6" class="accordion-collapse collapse" data-bs-parent="#faqTeslaModelY">
                            <div class="accordion-body">
                                No, the Personal Accident (PA) Cover for the Owner-Driver is mandatory for all vehicle owners. However, if a rider already holds a PA Cover of the stipulated amount for another vehicle they own, they can typically opt out of the PA cover for their new bike.
                            </div>
                        </div>
                    </div>

                    <div class="accordion-item">
                        <h3 class="accordion-header">
                            <button class="accordion-button collapsed" type="button" data-bs-toggle="collapse" data-bs-target="#q7" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="q7">
                                7. What is the penalty for riding a bike without mandatory insurance?
                            </button>
                        </h3>
                        <div id="q7" class="accordion-collapse collapse" data-bs-parent="#faqTeslaModelY">
                            <div class="accordion-body">
                                Riding a bike without at least a valid Third-Party Liability insurance is a legal offense. The penalty for the first offense is typically a fine of ₹2,000, and for subsequent offenses, the fine increases to ₹4,000, potentially along with community service or imprisonment, as per revised motor vehicle laws.
                            </div>
                        </div>
                    </div>

                    <div class="accordion-item">
                        <h3 class="accordion-header">
                            <button class="accordion-button collapsed" type="button" data-bs-toggle="collapse" data-bs-target="#q8" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="q8">
                                8. What is a "cashless claim"?
                            </button>
                        </h3>
                        <div id="q8" class="accordion-collapse collapse" data-bs-parent="#faqTeslaModelY">
                            <div class="accordion-body">
                                A cashless claim means that the insured person can take their damaged bike to a garage that is part of the insurer's network (a "network garage"). The insurer settles the repair bill directly with the garage, and the owner only pays for the deductibles and any non-covered expenses.
                            </div>
                        </div>
                    </div>

                    <div class="accordion-item">
                        <h3 class="accordion-header">
                            <button class="accordion-button collapsed" type="button" data-bs-toggle="collapse" data-bs-target="#q9" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="q9">
                                9. What are 'Consumables' in bike insurance?
                            </button>
                        </h3>
                        <div id="q9" class="accordion-collapse collapse" data-bs-parent="#faqTeslaModelY">
                            <div class="accordion-body">
                                Consumables refer to items used up during repair or replacement that are not covered under a standard policy. Examples include engine oil, nuts, bolts, screws, brake fluid, oil filters, and grease. The Consumables Cover add-on is needed to cover the cost of these items.
                            </div>
                        </div>
                    </div>

                    <div class="accordion-item">
                        <h3 class="accordion-header">
                            <button class="accordion-button collapsed" type="button" data-bs-toggle="collapse" data-bs-target="#q10" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="q10">
                                10. Can I transfer my bike insurance policy to a new owner?
                            </button>
                        </h3>
                        <div id="q10" class="accordion-collapse collapse" data-bs-parent="#faqTeslaModelY">
                            <div class="accordion-body">
                                Yes, when selling a bike, the existing insurance policy must be transferred to the new owner's name within 14 days of the bike's transfer. The previous owner is also entitled to claim an NCB retention certificate to use their accumulated discount on their next vehicle purchase.
                            </div>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>

